04306nam a22006015i 9789633865170DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222001hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97896338651707 a10.1515/97896338651702doi  a(DE-B1597)633360  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aHankiss, Elemér, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFears and Symbols :bAn Introduction to the Study of Western Civilization /cElemér Hankiss. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (333 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Fear and the Social Sciences -- tChapter Two. The World of Symbols -- tChapter Three. An Alien World? -- tChapter Four. The Garden of Eden -- tChapter Five. The Image of the World -- tChapter Six. The Moral Universe -- tChapter Seven. The World of Guilt -- tChapter Eight. The Rational World -- tChapter Nine. The World of Beauty -- tChapter Ten. The World of Play -- tChapter Eleven. The World of Jokes -- tChapter Twelve. The World of Trivialities -- tChapter Thirteen. Symbols and Civilization -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is a serious scholarly work that is, at the same time, somewhat unorthodox. On the one hand, it elaborates a systematic theory of civilization. It surveys the major theories of civilization and develops a new hypothesis, according to which existential fear has been a major factor in the generation of human culture. The author argues that in order to mitigate this fear and anxiety, human beings and communities have surrounded themselves not only with the walls of their houses and cities, with tools and weapons, laws and institutions, but also with protective spheres of symbols: myths and religions, values and belief systems, ideas and scientific theories, moral and practical rules of behavior, and a multitude of everyday rituals and trivialities. In a word, with the brilliant construct: civilization. It is, on the other hand, an unorthodox book in that it studies an unusually wide range of examples and shows that the struggle for safety and freedom, for a meaningful life and human dignity, is present not only in the great symbolic systems of humankind but also in the most trivial of everyday activities and aspects of human existence; in tragedies as well as jokes, in the sacred as well as the profane, in the symbolism of medieval cathedrals as well as in that of contemporary shopping malls, in the great drama of Sin and Salvation as well as in the trivial mythology of perfumes. Ultimately, our trivialities are not trivial at all.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978963386517040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633865170423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633865170/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK